# Constants Protocol

## 1. Rule: No Magic Strings or Numbers

Every domain-specific string or number with semantic meaning MUST be a named constant.

```typescript
// Bad
if (user.role === 'admin') { ... }
setTimeout(fn, 5000);

// Good
const USER_ROLES = { ADMIN: 'admin', EDITOR: 'editor' } as const;
const TIMEOUTS = { SESSION_REFRESH_MS: 5000 } as const;
if (user.role === USER_ROLES.ADMIN) { ... }
```

## 2. Storage Location

| Scope | Location |
|---|---|
| Single component | Co-locate above component in same file |
| Store-level | `src/store/<domain>/constants.ts` |
| Route paths | `src/router/routes.ts` |
| i18n namespace names | `src/lib/i18n/constants.ts` |

## 3. Pattern

```typescript
// as const — enables literal type inference
export const STATUS = {
    PENDING: 'pending',
    ACTIVE: 'active',
    INACTIVE: 'inactive',
} as const;

// Derive union type from const
export type Status = (typeof STATUS)[keyof typeof STATUS];
// Result: 'pending' | 'active' | 'inactive'
```

## 4. Anti-Patterns (FORBIDDEN)

- ❌ `enum` — use `as const` + type derivation instead.
- ❌ Duplicated string literals across files.
- ❌ Magic numbers in business logic without named constants.
- ❌ Boolean flags as function params — use options object or named constants.
